	(723, 'oc0300.2_28', '<h2>Strategies to Prevent Sexual Harassment in the Workplace</h2>\r\r<p>The Supreme Court’s rulings in <i>Ellerth</i> and <i>Faragher</i> create an incentive for employers to implement and enforce strong policies prohibiting harassment and effective complaint procedures. The rulings also create an incentive for employees to alert management about harassment before it becomes severe and pervasive. If employers and employees undertake these steps, unlawful harassment can often be prevented, thereby effectuating an important goal of the anti-discrimination statutes.</p>\r\r<p align="center">{{COURSE_IMAGE:960}}</p>\r\r<p>The best tool for eliminating sexual harassment is <b><i>prevention</i></b>. The following are examples of how {{LOCATION:NAME}} can do their part in eliminating/reducing sexual harassment in the workplace.</p>\r\r<h3>Policy and Complaint Procedure</h3>\r\r<p>It generally is necessary for employers to establish, publicize, and enforce anti-harassment policies and complaint {% if state == "CA" %}procedures; in California this also includes abusive conduct. {% else %}procedures. {% endif %}As the Supreme Court stated, “Title VII is designed to encourage the creation of anti-harassment policies and effective grievance mechanisms.” While the Court noted that this “is not necessary in every instance as a matter of law,” failure to do so will make it difficult for an employer to prove that it exercised reasonable care to prevent and correct harassment.<p> \r\r<P>{{LOCATION:NAME}} should provide every employee with a copy of their {{CUSTOM_POLICY_TITLE:1}}, and redistribute it periodically. The {{CUSTOM_POLICY_TITLE:1}} should be written in a way that will be understood by all employees in {{LOCATIONS:NAME}} workforce. Other measures to ensure effective dissemination of the {{CUSTOM_POLICY_TITLE:1}} include posting in central locations and incorporating them into their employee handbook. If feasible, {{LOCATION:NAME}} should provide training to all employees to ensure that they understand their rights and responsibilities.</p>\r\r<p>An anti-harassment policy and complaint procedure should contain, at a minimum, the following elements:</p>\r\r<div class="callout callout-blue">\r<ol>\r<li>A clear explanation of prohibited conduct;\r<li>Assurance that employees who make complaints of harassment or provide information related to such complaints will be protected against retaliation;\r<li>A clearly described complaint process that provides accessible avenues of complaint;\r<li>Assurance that the employer will protect the confidentiality of harassment complaints to the extent possible;\r<li>A complaint process that provides a prompt, thorough, and impartial investigation; and\r<li>Assurance that the employer will take immediate and appropriate corrective action when it determines that harassment has occurred.\r</ol></div>\r\r<p>The above 6 elements are explained in the following pages.</p>\r', 28, 170, 1, NULL, NULL),
	(724, 'oc0300.2_29', '<h4>#1: Prohibition Against Harassment</h4>\r\r<p>An employer’s policy should make clear that it will not tolerate harassment based on sex (with or without sexual conduct), race, color, religion, national origin, age, disability, and protected activity (i.e., opposition to prohibited discrimination or participation in the statutory complaint process). {% if state == "CA" %}In California this policy must also include abusive conduct. {% endif %}This prohibition should cover harassment by anyone in the workplace—supervisors, coworkers, or non-employees. Management should convey the seriousness of the prohibition. One way to do that is for the mandate to “come from the top,” i.e., from upper management.</p>\r\r<p align="center">{{COURSE_IMAGE:961}}</p>\r\r<p>The policy should encourage employees to report harassment <i>before</i> it becomes severe or pervasive. While isolated incidents of harassment generally do not violate federal law, a pattern of such incidents may be unlawful. Therefore, to discharge its duty of preventive care, the employer <i>must make clear</i> to employees that it will <b>stop</b> harassment {% if state == "CA" %}and abusive conduct {% endif %}before it rises to the level of a violation of {% if state == "CA" %}California and {% endif %}federal law.</p>\r\r<h4>#2: Protection Against Retaliation</h4>\r\r<p>An employer should make clear that there is <i>zero tolerance</i> for adverse treatment of employees because they report harassment{% if state == "CA" %}, abusive conduct,{% endif %} or provide information related to such complaints. An anti-harassment policy and complaint procedure will not be effective without such an assurance.</p>\r\r<p>Management should undertake whatever measures are necessary to ensure that retaliation does not occur.</p> \r\r<div class="callout callout-green">\r<h4>EXAMPLE:</h4>\r\r<p>When management investigates a complaint of harassment, the official who interviews the parties and witnesses should remind these individuals about the prohibition against retaliation. Management also should scrutinize employment decisions affecting the complainant and witnesses during and after the investigation to ensure that such decisions are not based on retaliatory motives.</p></div>\r', 29, 120, 1, NULL, NULL),
	(725, 'oc0300.2_30', '<h4>#3: Effective Complaint Process</h4>\r\r<p>An employer’s harassment{% if state == "CA" %}/abusive conduct{% endif %} complaint procedure should be designed to encourage victims to come forward. To that end, it should clearly explain the process and ensure that there are no unreasonable obstacles to complaints. A complaint procedure should not be rigid, since that could defeat the goal of preventing and correcting harassment{% if state == "CA" %} or abusive conduct{% endif %}. When an employee complains to management about alleged harassment{% if state == "CA" %} or abusive conduct{% endif %}, the employer is obligated to investigate the allegation regardless of whether it conforms to a particular format or is made in writing.</p>\r\r<p align="center">{{COURSE_IMAGE:962}}</p>\r\r<p>The complaint procedure should provide accessible points of contact for the initial complaint. A complaint process is <u>not</u> effective if employees are always required to complain first to their supervisors about alleged harassment{% if state == "CA" %} or abusive conduct{% endif %}, since the supervisor may be a harasser{% if state == "CA" %}/abuser{% endif %}. Moreover, reasonable care in preventing and correcting harassment{% if state == "CA" %} and/or abusive conduct{% endif %} requires an employer to instruct all supervisors to report complaints of harassment{% if state == "CA" %} and abusive conduct{% endif %} to appropriate officials.</p>\r\r<p>It is advisable for an employer to designate at least one official outside an employee’s chain of command to take complaints of harassment{% if state == "CA" %} and abusive conduct{% endif %}. For example, if the employer has an office of human resources, one or more officials in that office could be authorized to take complaints. Allowing an employee to bypass his or her chain of command provides additional assurance that the complaint will be handled in an impartial manner, since an employee who reports harassment{% if state == "CA" %} or abusive conduct{% endif %} by his or her supervisor may feel that officials within the chain of command will more readily believe the supervisor’s version of events.</p>\r\r<p>It also is important for an employer’s anti-harassment{% if state == "CA" %}/abusive conduct{% endif %} policy and complaint procedure to contain information about the time frames for filing charges of unlawful harassment {% if state == "CA" %}and/or abusive conduct to {% endif %}with the EEOC or state FEPAs and to explain that the deadline runs from the last date of unlawful harassment{% if state == "CA" %}/abusive conduct{% endif %}—not from the date that the complaint to the employer is resolved. While a prompt complaint process should make it feasible for an employee to delay deciding whether to file a charge until the complaint to the employer is resolved, he or she is not required to do so.</p>\r', 30, 140, 1, NULL, NULL),
	(726, 'oc0300.2_31', '<h4>#4: Confidentiality</h4>\r\r<p>An employer should make clear to employees that it will protect the confidentiality of harassment{% if state == "CA" %}/abusive conduct{% endif %} allegations to the extent possible. An employer cannot guarantee complete confidentiality, since it cannot conduct an effective investigation without revealing certain information to the alleged harasser{% if state == "CA" %}/abuser{% endif %} and potential witnesses. However, information about the allegation of harassment{% if state == "CA" %} or abusive conduct{% endif %} should be shared only with those who need to know about it. Records relating to harassment{% if state == "CA" %} or abusive conduct{% endif %} complaints should be kept confidential on the same basis.</p>\r\r<p align="center">{{COURSE_IMAGE:963}}</p>\r\r<p>A conflict between an employee’s desire for confidentiality and the employer’s duty to investigate may arise if an employee informs a supervisor about alleged harassment{% if state == "CA" %} or abusive conduct{% endif %}, but asks him or her to keep the matter confidential and take no action. Inaction by the supervisor in such circumstances could lead to employer liability. While it may seem reasonable to let the employee determine whether to pursue a complaint, <i>the employer must discharge its duty to prevent and correct harassment{% if state == "CA" %} or abusive conduct{% endif %}</i>. One mechanism to help avoid such conflicts would be for the employer to set up an informational phone line that employees could use to discuss questions or concerns about harassment{% if state == "CA" %} or abusive conduct{% endif %} on an anonymous basis.</p>', 31, 80, 1, NULL, NULL),
	(727, 'oc0300.2_32', '<h4>#5 Effective Investigative Process</h4>\r\r<p>Employers should set up a mechanism for a prompt, thorough, and impartial investigation into alleged harassment{% if state == "CA" %}/abusive conduct{% endif %}. As soon as management learns about alleged harassment{% if state == "CA" %} or abusive conduct{% endif %}, it should determine whether a detailed fact-finding investigation is necessary. For example, if the alleged harasser{% if state == "CA" %}/abuser{% endif %} does not deny the accusation, there would be no need to interview witnesses, and the employer could immediately determine appropriate corrective action.</p>\r\r<p>If a fact-finding investigation is necessary, it should be launched immediately. The amount of time that it will take to complete the investigation will depend on the particular circumstances. If, for example, multiple individuals were allegedly harassed{% if state == "CA" %} or abused{% endif %}, then it will take longer to interview the parties and witnesses.</p>\r\r<p align="center">{{COURSE_IMAGE:964}}</p>\r\r<p>It may be necessary to undertake intermediate measures before completing the investigation to ensure that further harassment does not occur.</p> \r\r<div class="callout callout-green">\r<h4>EXAMPLE:</h4>\r\r<p>Examples of such measures are making scheduling changes so as to avoid contact between the parties; transferring the alleged harasser{% if state == "CA" %}/abuser{% endif %}; or placing the alleged harasser{% if state == "CA" %}/abuser{% endif %} on non-disciplinary leave with pay pending the conclusion of the investigation.</p></div> \r\r<p>The complainant should <u>not</u> be involuntarily transferred or otherwise burdened, since such measures could constitute unlawful retaliation.</p>\r\r<p>Employers should ensure that the individual who conducts the investigation would objectively gather and consider the relevant facts. The alleged harasser{% if state == "CA" %}/abuser{% endif %} should <u>not</u> have supervisory authority over the individual who conducts the investigation and should <u>not</u> have any direct or indirect control over the investigation. The investigator should be well trained in the skills that are required for interviewing witnesses and evaluating credibility.</p>\r\r<h4>Reaching a Determination</h4>\r\r<p>Once all of the evidence is in, interviews are finalized, and credibility issues are resolved, management should make a determination as to whether harassment{% if state == "CA" %} or abusive conduct{% endif %} occurred. That determination could be made by the investigator, or by a management official who reviews the investigator’s report. The parties should be informed of the determination.</p>\r\r<p>In some circumstances, it may be difficult for management to reach a determination because of direct contradictions between the parties and a lack of documentary or eyewitness corroboration. In such cases, a credibility assessment may form the basis for a determination.</p>\r\r<p>If no determination can be made because the evidence is inconclusive, the employer should still undertake further preventive measures, such as training and monitoring.</p>', 32, 160, 1, NULL, NULL),
	(728, 'oc0300.2_33', '<h4>#6 Assurance of Immediate and Appropriate Corrective Action</h4>\r\r<p>Employers should make clear that it will undertake immediate and appropriate corrective action, including discipline, whenever it determines that harassment{% if state == "CA" %} or abusive conduct{% endif %} has occurred in violation of the employer’s policy. Management should inform both parties about these measures.</p>\r\r<p align="center">{{COURSE_IMAGE:965}}</p>\r\r<p>Remedial measures should be designed to stop the harassment{% if state == "CA" %} or abusive conduct{% endif %}, correct its effects on the employee, and ensure that the harassment{% if state == "CA" %} or abusive conduct{% endif %} does not recur. These remedial measures need not be those that the employee requests or prefers, as long as they are effective.</p>\r\r<div class="callout callout-red">\r<h4>ALERT:</h4>\r\r<p>In determining disciplinary measures, management should keep in mind that the employer could be found liable if the harassment{% if state == "CA" %} or abusive conduct{% endif %} does not stop. At the same time, management may have concerns that overly punitive measures may subject the employer to claims such as wrongful discharge, and may simply be inappropriate.</p></div>\r\r<p>To balance the competing concerns, disciplinary measures should be proportional to the seriousness of the offense. If the harassment{% if state == "CA" %} or abusive conduct{% endif %} was minor, such as a small number of “off-color” remarks by an individual with no prior history of similar misconduct, then counseling and an oral warning might be all that is necessary. On the other hand, if the harassment{% if state == "CA" %} or abusive conduct{% endif %} was severe or persistent, then suspension or discharge may be appropriate.</p>\r\r<p>Remedial measures should <u>not</u> adversely affect the complainant. Thus, for example, if it is necessary to separate the parties, then the <i>harasser{% if state == "CA" %}/abuser{% endif %}</i> should be transferred (unless the complainant prefers otherwise). Remedial responses that penalize the complainant could constitute unlawful retaliation and are not effective in correcting the harassment{% if state == "CA" %} or abusive conduct{% endif %}.</p>\r\r<p>Remedial measures also should correct the effects of the harassment{% if state == "CA" %} or abusive conduct{% endif %}. Such measures should be designed to put the employee in the position s/he would have been in had the misconduct not occurred.</p>\r\r<p>Examples of measures to stop harassment{% if state == "CA" %} or abusive conduct{% endif %} and ensure that it does not recur include but are not limited to:</p>\r\r<div class="callout callout-blue">\r<ul>\r<li>Oral or written warning or reprimand\r<li>Transfer or reassignment\r<li>Demotion\r<li>Reduction of wages\r<li>Suspension\r<li>Discharge\r<li>Training or counseling of harasser{% if state == "CA" %}/abuser{% endif %} to ensure that s/he understands why his or her conduct violated the employer’s anti-harassment{% if state == "CA" %}/abusive conduct{% endif %} policy\r<li>Monitoring of harasser{% if state == "CA" %}/abuser{% endif %} to ensure that harassment{% if state == "CA" %} and/or abusive conduct{% endif %} stops\r</ul></div>\r\r<p>Examples of measures to correct the effects of the harassment{% if state == "CA" %} and/or abusive conduct{% endif %} include but are not limited to:</p>\r\r<div class="callout callout-green">\r<ul>\r<li>Restoration of leave taken because of the harassment{% if state == "CA" %} and/or abusive conduct{% endif %}\r<li>Expungement of negative evaluation(s) in employee’s personnel file that arose from the harassment{% if state == "CA" %} and/or abusive conduct{% endif %}\r<li>Reinstatement\r<li>Apology by the harasser{% if state == "CA" %}/abuser{% endif %}\r<li>Monitoring treatment of employee to ensure that s/he is not subjected to retaliation by the harasser{% if state == "CA" %}/abuser{% endif %} or others in the workplace because of the complaint\r<li>Correction of any other harm caused by the harassment{% if state == "CA" %} and/or abusive conduct{% endif %} (e.g., compensation for losses)\r</ul></div>', 33, 190, 1, NULL, NULL),
	(729, 'oc0300.2_34', '<h2>Other Preventive and Corrective Measures</h2>\r\r<P>{{LOCATIONS:NAME}} responsibility to exercise reasonable care to prevent and correct harassment{% if state == "CA" %} and/or abusive conduct{% endif %} is <u>not</u> limited to implementing an anti-harassment{% if state == "CA" %}/abusive conduct{% endif %} policy and complaint procedure. As the Supreme Court stated, “the employer has a greater opportunity to guard against misconduct by supervisors than by common workers; employers have greater opportunity and incentive to screen them, train them, and monitor their performance.”</p> \r\r<p align="center">{{COURSE_IMAGE:966}}</p>\r\r<P>{{LOCATIONS:NAME}} duty to exercise due care includes instructing all of its supervisors and managers to address or report to appropriate officials complaints of harassment{% if state == "CA" %} and/or abusive conduct{% endif %} regardless of whether they are officially designated to take complaints and regardless of whether a complaint was framed in a way that conforms to the organization’s particular complaint procedures.</p> \r\r<div class="callout callout-green">\r<h4>EXAMPLE:</h4>\r\r<p>If an employee files an EEOC charge alleging unlawful harassment, {{LOCATION:NAME}} should launch an internal investigation even if the employee did not complain to management through its internal complaint process.</p></div>\r\r<p>Furthermore, due care requires management to correct harassment <i>regardless of whether an employee files an internal complaint</i>, if the conduct is clearly unwelcome.</p> \r\r<div class="callout callout-green">\r<h4>EXAMPLE:</h4>\r\r<p>If there are areas in the workplace with graffiti containing racial or sexual epithets, management should eliminate the graffiti and not wait for an internal complaint.</p></div>\r\r<P>{{LOCATION:NAME}} should ensure that its supervisors and managers understand their responsibilities under the organization’s anti-harassment{% if state == "CA" %}/abusive conduct{% endif %} policy and complaint procedure. Periodic training of those individuals can help achieve that result. Such training should explain the types of conduct that violate {{LOCATIONS:NAME}} anti-harassment{% if state == "CA" %}/abusive conduct{% endif %} policy; the seriousness of the policy; the responsibilities of supervisors and managers when they learn of alleged harassment{% if state == "CA" %} and/or abusive conduct{% endif %}; and the prohibition against retaliation. Supervisory personnel should be educated about their specific responsibilities. Rank and file employees should be cautioned against using peer pressure to discourage harassment{% if state == "CA" %} and/or abusive conduct{% endif %} victims from using the internal grievance procedure.</p>\r\r<P>{{LOCATION:NAME}} should keep track of its supervisors’ and managers’ conduct to make sure that they carry out their responsibilities under the organization’s anti-harassment{% if state == "CA" %}/abusive conduct{% endif %} program. For example, an employer could include such compliance in formal evaluations.</p>\r\r<p>Reasonable preventive measures include screening applicants for supervisory jobs to see if any have a record of engaging in harassment{% if state == "CA" %} and/or abusive conduct{% endif %}. If so, it may be necessary for {{LOCATION:NAME}} to reject a candidate on that basis or to take additional steps to prevent harassment{% if state == "CA" %} and/or abusive conduct{% endif %} by that individual.</p>\r\r<p>Finally, it is advisable for {{LOCATION:NAME}} to keep records of all complaints of harassment{% if state == "CA" %} and/or abusive conduct{% endif %}. Without such records, {{LOCATION:NAME}} could be unaware of a pattern of harassment{% if state == "CA" %} and/or abusive conduct{% endif %} by the same individual. Such a pattern would be relevant to credibility assessments and disciplinary measures.</p>', 34, 190, 1, NULL, NULL),
	(730, 'oc0300.2_35', '<h1 align="center">{{ORG:NAME}}</h1>\n<h2>Anti-Harassment and Discrimination Policy</h2>\n\n<p>The Company strives to create and maintain a work environment in which people are treated with dignity, decency and respect; characterized by mutual trust and the absence of intimidation and exploitation.  This is essential to our mission. The Company will not tolerate unlawful discrimination or harassment of any kind. Through enforcement and education of employees, we will seek to prevent and correct behavior that violates this policy.</p>\n\n<p>All employees, regardless of their positions, are covered by and are expected to comply with this policy and to take appropriate measures to ensure that prohibited conduct does not occur. Appropriate disciplinary action will be taken against any employee who violates this policy. Based upon the seriousness of the offense, disciplinary action may include verbal or written reprimand, suspension or immediate termination of employment.</p>\n\n<h2><i>Prohibited Conduct under this Policy</i></h2>\n\n<p>Harassment, including sexual harassment, is prohibited by federal and state laws. This policy prohibits harassment of any kind, and the company will take appropriate action swiftly to address any violations of this policy.  <b><u>Harassment is behavior that is unwelcome, humiliating, interferes with work performance and creates an intimidating, hostile or offensive work environment</u></b>.</p>\n\n<p>Sexual harassment includes unsolicited and unwelcome sexual advances, requests for sexual favors, or other verbal or physical conduct of a sexual nature, when such conduct:</p>\n\n<div class="callout callout-blue">\n<ul>\n<li>Is made explicitly or implicitly a term or condition of employment. \r<li>Is used as a basis for an employment decision. \r<li>Unreasonably interferes with an employee\'s work performance or creates an intimidating, hostile or otherwise offensive environment.\r</ul>\n</div>\n\n<p>Sexual harassment does not refer to behavior or occasional compliments of a socially acceptable nature. It refers to behavior that is unwelcome, that is personally offensive, that lowers morale and therefore interferes with work effectiveness. Sexual harassment may take different forms.</p>\n\n<p>Normal, courteous, mutually respectful, pleasant, non-coercive interactions between employees, including men and women, that is acceptable to and welcomed by both parties, is not considered to be harassment, including sexual harassment.</p>\n\n<p>There are basically two types of sexual harassment:</p>\n\n<div class="callout callout-green">\n<ul>\n<li>"Quid pro quo" harassment, where sexual advances are used as the basis for employment decisions and are directly linked to compliance. Therefore, only someone with the authority to grant such benefits can engage in quid pro quo harassment.   Example: A supervisor promising an employee a raise if she goes on a date with him. \r<li>"Hostile work environment," where the harassment creates an offensive and unpleasant working environment. Hostile work environment can be created by anyone in the work environment, whether it is supervisors, other employees or customers. Hostile environment harassment consists of verbiage of a sexual nature, unwelcome sexual materials or even unwelcome physical contact in the work environment.\n</ul></div>\r\r<h2><i>Retaliation</i></h2>\n\n<p>No hardship, loss of benefit, or penalty may be imposed on an employee as punishment for:</p>\n\n<div class="callout callout-yellow">\n<ul>\n<li>Filing or responding to a bona fide complaint of discrimination or harassment. \r<li>Appearing as a witness in the investigation of a complaint. \r<li>Serving as an investigator.\r</ul></div>\n\n<p>Retaliation or attempted retaliation is a violation of this policy and anyone who does so will be subject to severe sanctions up to and including termination.</p>\n\n<h2>Reports, Complaints, Investigations Policy</h2>\n\n<p>Any employee or applicant for employment of the Company who has been subjected to discrimination, harassment or retaliation in violation of Company policy or applicable law, or who has witnessed or is aware of any such violation, should report such violation to The Company as soon as possible.</p>\n\n<p>Generally, you should report any such violation to your supervisor or manager.  However, if your supervisor or manager is the person who committed the violation, or if you do not wish to report the violation to your supervisor or manager for any other reason, you should report the violation to the Director of Human Resources.</p>\n\n<p><b><u>A supervisor, who receives a harassment or discrimination complaint, must immediately notify the Human Resources Department and refrain from investigating until discussing with Human Resources.  If a supervisor/manager becomes aware that harassment or discrimination is occurring from observation or another way, they must immediately report it.</u></b></p>\n\n<p>Employees may report the violation either orally or in writing.  In either event, state the specific details of the alleged discrimination, harassment or retaliation including:</p>\n\n<div class="callout callout-blue">\n<ul>\n<li>the date(s) and time(s) of the statements or conduct complained of; \r<li>the names of the individual(s) involved; \r<li>a description of the conduct complained of, using direct quotations whenever possible; \r<li>the name(s) of any witness(es); \r<li>a description or copy of any evidence (such as notes, pictures, cartoons);\n</ul></div>\n\n<p>Any person electing to use this complaint resolution process will be treated courteously, the problem handled swiftly and as confidentially as feasible in light of the need to take appropriate corrective action. Filing groundless or malicious complaints is an abuse of this policy.</p>\n\n<p>During the complaint process, while the confidentiality of the information received, the privacy of the individuals involved, and the wishes of the complaining person regarding action cannot be guaranteed in every instance, they will be protected to as great a degree as is possible and considered in the context of the company’s obligation to act upon and investigate the charge and the right of the charged party to obtain information.</p>\n\n<p>Upon receiving the complaint or being advised of a potential violation of this policy, the Director of Human Resources will notify the CEO as appropriate and review and investigate the complaint.</p>\n\n<p>After receiving the complaint, the Director of Human Resources will:</p>\n\n<div class="callout callout-green">\n<ol>\n<li>Notify the person(s) charged [hereafter referred to as "respondent(s)”] of a complaint.\r<li>Initiate investigating to determine if there is reasonable basis that policy violation occurred.\r<li>During the investigation, the Director of Human Resources, legal counsel and/or other management employee(s), will interview the complainant, the respondent and any witnesses to determine whether the alleged conduct occurred. \r<li>Within 15 business days of the complaint, the Director of Human Resources or delegate will conclude the investigation and submit findings to the CEO.  If further investigation is needed, an update will be sent to complainant and the respondent with reason for delay\r<li>If it is determined that violation of policy has occurred, appropriate disciplinary action will be taken depending on the following factors: \r	<ol type="a">\r<li>The severity, frequency and pervasiveness of the conduct; \n<li>Prior complaints made against the respondent; \r<li>The quality of the evidence (first-hand knowledge, credible corroboration etc.). \n	</ol>\r<li>If the investigation is inconclusive or it is determined that there has been no violation of policy, but some problematic conduct is revealed, preventative action may be taken. \r<li>The Director of Human Resources will meet with the complainant and respondent separately in order to notify them of the findings of the and to inform them of the action being taken. \n</ol></div>\n\r\n<h1>Summary</h1>\r\r<p>Now that you have completed this course you should better understand the pervasive nature of sexual harassment{% if state == "CA" %} and/or abusive conduct{% endif %} in the workplace. You have learned both the federal definition and {{LOCATION:STATES_LONGNAME}} definition of sexual harassment{% if state == "CA" %} and abusive conduct{% endif %} and should be able to provide information and support to {{LOCATIONS:NAME}} employees. You should also understand {{LOCATIONS:NAME}} liability as an employer, including supervisors, other employees, and other individuals.</p>  \r\r<p>This course is <u>not</u> intended to be a Sexual Harassment{% if state == "CA" %}/Abusive Conduct{% endif %} Prevention Program, however, it does provide guidance on creating and implementing one.</p>\r\r<p>You have also read {{LOCATIONS:NAME}} specific {{CUSTOM_POLICY_TITLE:1}} and you must as part of passing the exam, attest that you understand this policy. As a supervisor you must understand {{LOCATIONS:NAME}} {{CUSTOM_POLICY_TITLE:1}} at an administrative level and be able to support it, educate subordinates, report incidents, but more importantly, be vigilant about noticing anything that can be construed as sexual harassment{% if state == "CA" %} and/or abusive conduct{% endif %} and take immediate action to prevent an incident. Remember that <b><i>prevention</i></b> is the best way to eradicate sexual harassment{% if state == "CA" %} and abusive conduct{% endif %} in the workplace.</p>', 35, 300, 1, NULL, NULL);
